    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/validation/stiffness-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — FEA vs. experimental (N=11)",
      "description": "Construct stiffness predicted by the FEA ensemble was compared against N=11 physical test specimens across two independent laboratories. The mean experimental stiffness was 142.3 N/mm (SD 8.7 N/mm). FEA predicted 138.1 N/mm, yielding a relative difference of 2.95%, well within the pre-specified 10% acceptance bound. The validation metric E/uval was computed as 0.81, below the 1.96 threshold. The Ansys 2023 R1 model, the FDA in-house implicit solver model, and the DePuy Synthes proprietary FEA model were each executed under identical boundary conditions replicating ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. Specimen-to-specimen variability was characterised via coefficient of variation (CV = 6.1%). Mesh convergence had been confirmed separately (GCI < 2% on stiffness QoI). Laboratory A contributed six specimens; Laboratory B contributed five. Cross-laboratory repeatability was assessed via two-sample t-test (p = 0.43), indicating no statistically significant inter-laboratory bias. Material properties were drawn from certified coupon test data supplied by the manufacturer and ingested into the model via the validated material property pipeline documented in report NGA-MAT-2023-04. All three FEA codes produced stiffness predictions within 4% of each other, confirming code-independence of the result. The validation activity was conducted between 2023-09-11 and 2023-11-22 under protocol NGA-VAL-PROT-001 Rev B.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/data/lab-a-compression-bending-n6"
    },
    {
